While you alone bear the weight of Rome's affairs,
so vast and varied in their scope;
while you defend the public weal with arms,
and adorn it with morals and laws;
shall not the lengthy letter be a crime
that steals even a single moment from Caesar's time? --Francis In person, Horace was short and fat. He described himself in this way in his Satires [970], and Augustus also mentioned it in a letter: "Dionysius has brought me your small volume. Although its size is not to blame on you, I shall judge it favourably." You appear to be intimidated by the prospect that your published works may surpass your own abilities.
